-- Hong Kong shares down as weak China factory activity saps confidence
-- By Natalie Thomas
-- Mon May 05, 2014 04:06AM EDT
-- None



BEIJING, May 5 (Reuters) - Hong Kong shares finished lower on Monday, after a private survey showed mainland manufacturing activity contracting for a fourth straight month, triggering a sell-off across the board.

The Hang Seng Index <.HSI> closed down 1.3 percent. The China Enterprises Index <.HSCE> of the leading offshore Chinese listings in Hong Kong was down 0.6 percent.  The HSBC/Markit purchasing managers' index (PMI) for April came in at 48.1 on Monday, lower than a preliminary reading of 48.3, though up slightly from an eight-month low of 48.0 in March. [ID:nB9N0MU00Q] Property stocks were some of the heaviest hit after pessimistic comments made by a top executive from the mainland's largest listed developer were leaked to the press over the holiday weekend.